    "reasoning": "The specification requires implementing a Finite State Machine (FSM) with inputs (clk, resetn, x, y) and outputs (f, g).\n\n**FSM State Definition:**\n1. **State A (Beginning State):** Initial state when resetn is asserted (active low reset).\n2. **Transition from A:** When resetn de-asserts (goes high), FSM enters a state where $f=1$ for one clock cycle.\n3. **State for Monitoring x (after f=1):** The FSM must monitor $x$ for the sequence 1, 0, 1 in three successive cycles. This requires tracking the last two values of $x$.\n4. **State for Monitoring y (after x sequence):** Once $x$ sequence (1, 0, 1) is met, $g$ is set to 1 on the *following* clock cycle. While $g=1$, the FSM monitors $y$. If $y=1$ within at most two clock cycles, $g$ stays 1 permanently. If $y$ does not become 1 within two cycles, $g$ becomes 0 permanently.\n\n**State Machine Design:**\nWe need enough states to track:\n1. Reset state (State A).\n2. F-pulse state (State B).\n3. Tracking $x$ sequence (e.g., waiting for 1, waiting for 0, waiting for 1).\n4. Monitoring $y$ for permanent $g=1$ or $g=0$.\n\nLet's define states:\n*   **STATE_A (Initial/Reset):** $\\text{resetn}$ is low, or the machine is reset.\n*   **STATE_B (F_Pulse):** $\\text{resetn}$ just went high. $f=1$ this cycle.\n*   **STATE_X1 (x=1):** Received first '1' of the sequence (1, 0, 1).\n*   **STATE_X0 (x=0):** Received '0' after '1'.\n*   **STATE_X1_Done (x=1):** Received '1' after '1, 0'. Triggers $g=1$ next cycle.\n*   **STATE_Y_WAIT_1 (g=1, waiting for y=1):** $g$ is high. Waiting for $y=1$ (Cycle 1 of 2).\n*   **STATE_Y_WAIT_2 (g=1, waiting for y=1):** $g$ is high. Waiting for $y=1$ (Cycle 2 of 2).\n*   **STATE_Y_PERM_HIGH (g=1 permanently):** $y=1$ was detected within 2 cycles.\n*   **STATE_Y_PERM_LOW (g=0 permanently):** 2 cycles passed without $y=1$.\n\n**State Transitions Logic:**\n1.  **Reset:** If $\\text{resetn} == 0$, $\\text{state} = \text{STATE_A}$.\n2.  **From STATE_A:** If $\\text{resetn} == 1$, $\\text{state_next} = \text{STATE_B}$.\n3.  **From STATE_B (F_Pulse):** $f=1$. $\\text{state_next} = \text{STATE_X1}$ (Start monitoring $x$).\n4.  **From STATE_X1 (Received $x=1$):** If $x=1$, stay in $\\text{STATE_X1}$. If $x=0$, move to $\\text{STATE_X0}$.\n5.  **From STATE_X0 (Received $x=0$):** If $x=1$, move to $\\text{STATE_X1_Done}$. If $x=0$, reset sequence, go to $\\text{STATE_X1}$.\n6.  **From STATE_X1_Done (x sequence complete):** $g=1$ on next cycle. $\\text{state_next} = \text{STATE_Y_WAIT_1}$.\n7.  **From STATE_Y_WAIT_1 (g=1):** If $y=1$, $\\text{state_next} = \text{STATE_Y_PERM_HIGH}$. If $y=0$, $\\text{state_next} = \text{STATE_Y_WAIT_2}$.\n8.  **From STATE_Y_WAIT_2 (g=1):** If $y=1$, $\\text{state_next} = \text{STATE_Y_PERM_HIGH}$. If $y=0$, $\\text{state_next} = \text{STATE_Y_PERM_LOW}$.\n9.  **From STATE_Y_PERM_HIGH:** Stay here, $g=1$ permanently.\n10. **From STATE_Y_PERM_LOW:** Stay here, $g=0$ permanently.\n\n**Output Logic (f and g):**\n*   $f$: $f=1$ only in $\\text{STATE_B}$. Otherwise $f=0$.\n*   $g$: $g=1$ in $\\text{STATE_X1_Done}$ (next cycle), $\\text{STATE_Y_WAIT_1}$, $\\text{STATE_Y_WAIT_2}$, $\\text{STATE_Y_PERM_HIGH}$. $g=0$ otherwise (including $\\text{STATE_Y_PERM_LOW}$). \n\n**Implementation Details & Advice:**\n1.  **State Encoding:** Use `localparam` for state definitions. Since we need about 8 states, 3 bits are sufficient (2^3=8).\n2.  **Reset Handling:** The reset is asynchronous/synchronous active-low. The FSM logic handles this by defaulting to STATE_A when $\\text{resetn}=0$.\n3.  **Initialization:** All sequential logic (state register) must be initialized in an `initial` block to avoid indeterminate values, as required.\n4.  **Combinational Logic:** Use `always @(*)` for all next-state and output logic.\n5.  **Syntax Safety:** Ensure proper use of `case` statements and avoid disallowed keywords.\n\n**Refining g output timing:** The requirement states: 'g should be set to 1 on the *following* clock cycle' after the $x$ sequence. This means the transition *to* the monitoring state must set the condition for $g=1$ next cycle. I will use a dedicated state for the $g=1$ pulse that immediately follows the $x$ sequence completion, or handle it by setting the state and allowing the output logic to capture it.",
    "module": "module TopModule (\n    input  logic clk,\n    input  logic resetn,\n    input  logic x,\n    input  logic y,\n    output logic f,\n    output logic g\n);\n\n    // --- State Definitions ---\n    // Need at least 8 states (A, B, X1, X0, X1_Done, Y1, Y2, Y_Low)\n    typedef enum logic [2:0] {\n        STATE_A,      // Initial state / Reset\n        STATE_B,      // F=1 pulse cycle\n        STATE_X1,     // Saw x=1 (Start sequence)\n        STATE_X0,     // Saw x=0 (after x=1)\n        STATE_X1_Done,// Saw x=1, 0, 1. G=1 next cycle.\n        STATE_Y_WAIT_1, // G=1, waiting for y=1 (Cycle 1)\n        STATE_Y_WAIT_2, // G=1, waiting for y=1 (Cycle 2)\n        STATE_Y_PERM_HIGH, // G=1 permanently\n        STATE_Y_PERM_LOW  // G=0 permanently\n    } state_t;\n\n    // --- Registers ---\n    state_t state_reg;\n    state_t state_next;\n\n    // Initialize state register to the reset state\n    initial begin\n        state_reg = STATE_A;\n    end\n\n    // --- Sequential Logic (State Register) ---\n    always @(posedge clk)\n    begin\n        if (!resetn) begin\n            state_reg <= STATE_A;\n        end else begin\n            state_reg <= state_next;\n        end\n    end\n\n    // --- Combinational Logic (Next State Logic) ---\n    always @(*)\n    begin\n        state_next = state_reg;\n\n        case (state_reg)\n            STATE_A: begin\n                if (resetn) begin\n                    // Transition to F pulse state upon reset de-assertion\n                    state_next = STATE_B;\n                end\n            end\n\n            STATE_B: begin\n                // F pulse done, start monitoring X sequence\n                state_next = STATE_X1; \n            end\n\n            STATE_X1: begin // Last seen x=1\n                if (x == 1'b1) begin\n                    state_next = STATE_X1; // 1 -> 1\n                end else begin // x=0\n                    state_next = STATE_X0; // 1 -> 0\n                end\n            end\n\n            STATE_X0: begin // Last seen x=0\n                if (x == 1'b1) begin\n                    // Sequence 1, 0, 1 complete. G=1 on next cycle.\n                    state_next = STATE_X1_Done;\n                end else begin // x=0\n                    // Sequence broken. Restart sequence check, last seen x=0\n                    state_next = STATE_X0;\n                end\n            end\n\n            STATE_X1_Done: begin\n                // X sequence complete. G=1 next cycle. Start monitoring Y.\n                state_next = STATE_Y_WAIT_1;\n            end\n\n            STATE_Y_WAIT_1: begin // G=1 active. Cycle 1 of 2.\n                if (y == 1'b1) begin\n                    state_next = STATE_Y_PERM_HIGH; // Y found early\n                end else begin\n                    state_next = STATE_Y_WAIT_2; // Continue waiting\n                end\n            end\n\n            STATE_Y_WAIT_2: begin // G=1 active. Cycle 2 of 2.\n                if (y == 1'b1) begin\n                    state_next = STATE_Y_PERM_HIGH; // Y found within 2 cycles\n                end else begin\n                    state_next = STATE_Y_PERM_LOW; // Y not found within 2 cycles\n                end\n            end\n\n            STATE_Y_PERM_HIGH: begin\n                state_next = STATE_Y_PERM_HIGH; // Stay high\n            end\n\n            STATE_Y_PERM_LOW: begin\n                state_next = STATE_Y_PERM_LOW; // Stay low\n            end\n\n            default: begin\n                state_next = STATE_A; // Safety default\n            end\n        endcase\n    end\n\n    // --- Output Logic ---\n    // f is high only for one cycle after reset de-assertion\n    assign f = (state_reg == STATE_B) ? 1'b1 : 1'b0;\n\n    // g is high during the X_Done state transition (next cycle), and while in Y_WAIT_1/2 or Y_PERM_HIGH\n    assign g = (state_reg == STATE_X1_Done) || \n                 (state_reg == STATE_Y_WAIT_1) || \n                 (state_reg == STATE_Y_WAIT_2) || \n                 (state_reg == STATE_Y_PERM_HIGH) ? 1'b1 : 1'b0;\n\nendmodule"
}
[2026-05-14 15:12:05,515 - mage.rtl_generator - INFO] RTL generator input message: [ChatMessage(role=<MessageRole.SYSTEM: 'system'>, additional_kwargs={}, blocks=[TextBlock(block_type='text', text='\nYou are an expert in RTL design. You can always write SystemVerilog code with no syntax errors and always reach correct functionality.\n')]), ChatMessage(role=<MessageRole.USER: 'user'>, additional_kwargs={}, blocks=[TextBlock(block_type='text', text='\nPlease write a module in SystemVerilog RTL language regarding to the given natural language specification.\nTry to understand the requirements above and give reasoning steps in natural language to achieve it.\nIn addition, try to give advice to avoid syntax error.\nAn SystemVerilog RTL module always starts with a line starting with the keyword \'module\' followed by the module name.\nIt ends with the keyword \'endmodule\'.\n\n[Hints]:\nFor implementing kmap (Karnaugh map), you need to think step by step.\nCarefully example how the kmap in input_spec specifies the order of the inputs.\nNote that x[i] in x[N:1] means x[i-1] in x[N-1:0].\nThen find the inputs corresponding to output=1, 0, and don\'t-care for each case.\n\nNote in Verilog, for a signal "logic x[M:N]" where M > N, you CANNOT reversely select bits from it like x[1:2];\nInstead, you should use concatations like {x[1], x[2]}.\n\nThe module interface should EXACTLY MATCH module_interface if given.\nOtherwise, should EXACTLY MATCH with the description in input_spec.\n(Including the module name, input/output ports names, and their types)\n\n\n\nHere are some examples of RTL SystemVerilog code:\nExample 1:\n<example>\n    <input_spec>\n        Implement the SystemVerilog module based on the following description.\n        Assume that sigals are positive clock/clk triggered unless otherwise stated.\n\n        The module should implement a XOR gate.\n    </input_spec>\n    <module>\n        module TopModule(\n            input  logic in0,\n            input  logic in1,\n            output logic out\n        );\n\n            assign out = in0 ^ in1;\n\n        endmodule\n    </module>\n</example>\nExample 2:\n<example>\n    <input_spec>\n        Implement the SystemVerilog module based on the following description.\n        Assume that sigals are positive clock/clk triggered unless otherwise stated.\n\n        The module should implement an 8-bit registered incrementer.\n        The 8-bit input is first registered and then incremented by one on the next cycle.\n        The reset input is active high synchronous and should reset the output to zero.\n    </input_spec>\n    <module>\n        module TopModule(\n            input  logic       clk,\n            input  logic       reset,\n            input  logic [7:0] in_,\n            output logic [7:0] out\n        );\n\n            // Sequential logic\n            logic [7:0] reg_out;\n            always @( posedge clk ) begin\n                if ( reset )\n                reg_out <= 0;\n                else\n                reg_out <= in_;\n            end\n\n            // Combinational logic\n            logic [7:0] temp_wire;\n            always @(*) begin\n                temp_wire = reg_out + 1;\n            end\n\n            // Structural connections\n            assign out = temp_wire;\n\n        endmodule\n    </module>\n</example>\nExample 3:\n<example>\n    <input_spec>\n        Implement the SystemVerilog module based on the following description.\n        Assume that sigals are positive clock/clk triggered unless otherwise stated.\n\n        The module should implement an n-bit registered incrementer where the bitwidth is specified by the parameter nbits.\n        The n-bit input is first registered and then incremented by one on the next cycle.\n        The reset input is active high synchronous and should reset the output to zero.\n    </input_spec>\n    <module>\n        module TopModule #(\n            parameter nbits\n        )(\n            input  logic             clk,\n            input  logic             reset,\n            input  logic [nbits-1:0] in_,\n            output logic [nbits-1:0] out\n        );\n\n            // Sequential logic\n            logic [nbits-1:0] reg_out;\n            always @( posedge clk ) begin\n                if ( reset )\n                reg_out <= 0;\n                else\n                reg_out <= in_;\n            end\n\n            // Combinational logic\n            logic [nbits-1:0] temp_wire;\n            always @(*) begin\n                temp_wire = reg_out + 1;\n            end\n\n            // Structural connections\n            assign out = temp_wire;\n\n        endmodule\n    </module>\n</example>\nExample 4:\n<example>\n    <input_spec>\n        Implement the SystemVerilog module based on the following description.\n        Assume that sigals are positive clock/clk triggered unless otherwise stated.\n\n        Build a finite-state machine that takes as input a serial bit stream,\n            and outputs a one whenever the bit stream contains two consecutive one\'s.\n        The output is one on the cycle _after_ there are two consecutive one\'s.\n        The reset input is active high synchronous,\n            and should reset the finite-state machine to an appropriate initial state.\n    </input_spec>\n    <module>\n        module TopModule(\n            input  logic clk,\n            input  logic reset,\n            input  logic in_,\n            output logic out\n        );\n\n            // State enum\n            localparam STATE_A = 2\'b00;\n            localparam STATE_B = 2\'b01;\n            localparam STATE_C = 2\'b10;\n\n            // State register\n            logic [1:0] state;\n            logic [1:0] state_next;\n            always @(posedge clk) begin\n                if ( reset )\n                state <= STATE_A;\n                else\n                state <= state_next;\n            end\n\n            // Next state combinational logic\n            always @(*) begin\n                state_next = state;\n                case ( state )\n                STATE_A: state_next = ( in_ ) ? STATE_B : STATE_A;\n                STATE_B: state_next = ( in_ ) ? STATE_C : STATE_A;\n                STATE_C: state_next = ( in_ ) ? STATE_C : STATE_A;\n                endcase\n            end\n\n            // Output combinational logic\n            always @(*) begin\n                out = 1\'b0;\n                case ( state )\n                STATE_A: out = 1\'b0;\n                STATE_B: out = 1\'b0;\n                STATE_C: out = 1\'b1;\n                endcase\n            end\n\n        endmodule\n    </module>\n</example>\n\n<input_spec>\n\nI would like you to implement a module named TopModule with the following\ninterface. All input and output ports are one bit unless otherwise\nspecified.\n\n - input  clk\n - input  resetn\n - input  x\n - input  y\n - output f\n - output g\n\nConsider a finite state machine that is used to control some type of\nmotor. The FSM has inputs x and y, which come from the motor, and\nproduces outputs f and g, which control the motor. There is also a clock\ninput called clk and a reset input (synchronous, active low) called\nresetn. The FSM has to work as follows. As long as the reset input is\nasserted, the FSM stays in a beginning state, called state A. When the\nreset signal is de-asserted, then after the next clock edge the FSM has\nto set the output f to 1 for one clock cycle. Then, the FSM has to\nmonitor the x input. When x has produced the values 1, 0, 1 in three\nsuccessive clock cycles, then g should be set to 1 on the following clock\ncycle. While maintaining g = 1 the FSM has to monitor the y input. If y\nhas the value 1 within at most two clock cycles, then the FSM should\nmaintain g = 1 permanently (that is, until reset). But if y does not\nbecome 1 within two clock cycles, then the FSM should set g = 0\npermanently (until reset). Assume all sequential logic is triggered on\nthe positive edge of the clock.\n\n\n</input_spec>\n')]), ChatMessage(role=<MessageRole.USER: 'user'>, additional_kwargs={}, blocks=[TextBlock(block_type='text', text='\nAnother agent has generated a testbench regarding the given input_spec:\n<testbench>\n`timescale 1 ps/1 ps\n\n`define OK 12\n`define INCORRECT 13\n\n\nmodule stimulus_gen (\n\tinput clk,\n\toutput logic resetn,\n\toutput logic x, y\n);\n\n\tinitial begin\n\t\tresetn = 0;\n\t\tx = 0;\n\t\ty = 0;\n\t\t@(posedge clk);\n\t\t@(posedge clk);\n\t\tresetn = 1;\n\t\trepeat(500) @(negedge clk) begin\n\t\t\tresetn <= ($random & 31) != 0;\n\t\t\t{x,y} <= $random;\n\t\tend\n\t\t\n\t\t#1 $finish;\n\tend\n\nendmodule\n\n// Assuming RefModule and TopModule exist and are correctly implemented elsewhere\n// For the testbench to compile, we define placeholders for them.\nmodule RefModule (\n    input logic clk,\n    input logic resetn,\n    input logic x,\n    input logic y,\n    output logic f,\n    output logic g\n);\n// Placeholder implementation\nassign f = 0;\nassign g = 0;\nendmodule\n\nmodule TopModule (\n    input logic clk,\n    input logic resetn,\n    input logic x,\n    input logic y,\n    output logic f,\n    output logic g\n);\n// Placeholder implementation\nassign f = 0;\nassign g = 0;\nendmodule\n\n\nmodule tb();\n\n\ttypedef struct packed {\n\t\tint errors;\n\t\tint errortime;\n\t\tint errors_f;\n\t\tint errortime_f;\n\t\tint errors_g;\n\t\tint errortime_g;\n\t\tint clocks;\n\t} stats;\n\t\n\tstats stats1;\n\t\n\t// --- Queue Definitions for Mismatch Reporting ---\n\t// Maximum queue size constraint: NEVER set MAX_QUEUE_SIZE > 10.\n\tlocalparam MAX_QUEUE_SIZE = 10;\n\t\n\treg [1:0] input_clk_queue [$];\n\treg [1:0] input_resetn_queue [$];\n\treg [1:0] input_x_queue [$];\n\treg [1:0] input_y_queue [$];\n\treg [1:0] got_f_queue [$];\n\treg [1:0] got_g_queue [$];\n\treg [1:0] golden_f_queue [$];\n\treg [1:0] golden_g_queue [$];\n\treg reset_queue [$];\n\n\t// --- Original Testbench Signals ---\n\twire[511:0] wavedrom_title;\n\twire wavedrom_enable;\n\tint wavedrom_hide_after_time;\n\t\n\treg clk=0;\n\tinitial forever\n\t\thalfperiod_clk_gen: #5 clk = ~clk;\n\n\tlogic resetn;\n\tlogic x;\n\tlogic y;\n\tlogic f_ref;\n\tlogic f_dut;\n\tlogic g_ref;\n\tlogic g_dut;\n\n\t// --- Testbench Setup ---\n\tinitial begin \n\t\t$dumpfile("wave.vcd");\n\t\t$dumpvars(1, stim1.clk, tb_mismatch ,clk,resetn,x,y,f_ref,f_dut,g_ref,g_dut );\n\tend\n\n\twire tb_match; // Verification\n\twire tb_mismatch = ~tb_match;\n\t\n\t// Instantiate Stimulus Generator\n\tstimulus_gen stim1 (\n\t\t.clk, \n\t\t.resetn, \n\t\tx, \n\t\ty );\n\t\n\t// Instantiate Reference Model\t\n\tRefModule good1 (\n\t\t.clk, \n\t\t.resetn, \n\t\tx, \n\t\ty, \n\t\tf(f_ref), \n\t\tg(g_ref) );\n\t\n\t// Instantiate DUT\n\tTopModule top_module1 (\n\t\t.clk, \n\t\t.resetn, \n\t\tx, \n\t\ty, \n\t\tf(f_dut), \n\t\tg(g_dut) );\n\n\t// --- Timing Task (Kept for functional compatibility) ---\n\tbit strobe = 0;\n\ttask wait_for_end_of_timestep;\n\t\trepeat(5) begin\n\t\t\tstrobe <= !strobe;  // Try to delay until the very end of the time step.\n\t\t\t@(strobe);\n\t\tend\ntask\n\n\t// --- Mismatch Queueing and Verification Logic ---\n\t// We need a flag to track if the first mismatch has already been reported\n\treg mismatch_reported = 0;\n\n\talways @(posedge clk, negedge clk) begin\n\t\t// 1. Queue Management: Shift and Push\n\t\tif (input_clk_queue.size() >= MAX_QUEUE_SIZE - 1) begin\n\t\t\tinput_clk_queue.delete(0);\n\t\t\tinput_resetn_queue.delete(0);\n\t\t\tinput_x_queue.delete(0);\n\t\t\tinput_y_queue.delete(0);\n\t\t\tgot_f_queue.delete(0);\n\t\t\tgot_g_queue.delete(0);\n\t\t\tgolden_f_queue.delete(0);\n\t\t\tgolden_g_queue.delete(0);\n\t\t\treset_queue.delete(0);\n\t\tend\n\n\t\t// Push current cycle values\n\t\tinput_clk_queue.push_back(clk);\n\t\tinput_resetn_queue.push_back(resetn);\n\t\tinput_x_queue.push_back(x);\n\t\tinput_y_queue.push_back(y);\n\t\tgot_f_queue.push_back(f_dut);\n\t\tgot_g_queue.push_back(g_dut);\n\t\tgolden_f_queue.push_back(f_ref);\n\t\tgolden_g_queue.push_back(g_ref);\n\t\treset_queue.push_back(resetn);\n\n\t\t// 2. Mismatch Detection (Original Logic Replacement)\n\t\t// The original check: tb_match = ({ f_ref, g_ref } === ( { f_ref, g_ref } ^ { f_dut, g_dut } ^ { f_ref, g_ref } ));\n\t\t// Simplified match check: {f_ref, g_ref} === {f_dut, g_dut}\n\t\ttb_match = ( { f_ref, g_ref } === { f_dut, g_dut } );\n\n\t\t// 3. Error Counting (Original Logic Maintained)\n\t\tstats1.clocks++;\n\t\t\n\t\t// Count general mismatches\n\t\tif (!tb_match) begin\n\t\t\tif (stats1.errors == 0) stats1.errortime = $time;\n\t\t\tstats1.errors++;\n\t\tend\n\t\t\n\t\t// Count f mismatches\n\t\tif (f_ref !== f_dut) \n\t\tbegin \n\t\t\tif (stats1.errors_f == 0) stats1.errortime_f = $time;\n\t\t\tstats1.errors_f = stats1.errors_f+1\'b1;\n\t\tend\n\t\t\n\t\t// Count g mismatches\n\t\tif (g_ref !== g_dut) \n\t\tbegin \n\t\t\tif (stats1.errors_g == 0) stats1.errortime_g = $time;\n\t\t\tstats1.errors_g = stats1.errors_g+1\'b1;\n\t\tend\n\t\t\n\t\t// 4. First Mismatch Reporting (Queue Display)\n\t\tif (!tb_match && mismatch_reported == 0) begin\n\t\t\tmismatch_reported = 1;\n\t\t\t$display("====================================================================");\n\t\t\t$display("!!! FIRST MISMATCH DETECTED AT TIME %0t !!!", $time);\n\t\t\t$display("--- Displaying Last %d Cycles of History ---", input_clk_queue.size());\n\t\t\t\n\t\t\t// Display loop (Note: Iterating backwards from current size-1 to 0 shows history correctly if size is MAX_QUEUE_SIZE)\n\t\t\tfor (int i = 0; i < input_clk_queue.size(); i++) begin\n\t\t\t\t// Determine index relative to the end of the stored data for clear history viewing\n\t\t\t\tint history_idx = input_clk_queue.size() - 1 - i;\n\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t$display("Cycle Index %d (Time T-%0d):", history_idx, input_clk_queue.size() - 1 - history_idx);\n\t\t\t\t$display("  Reset Signal (resetn): %b", reset_queue[history_idx]);\n\t\t\t\t$display("  Inputs (x, y): %b, %b